					Full Description



United States Antimony Corporation, incorporated on January 14, 1970, is engaged in the production and sale of antimony, silver, gold and zeolite products. The Company is a mining, transportation, milling, smelting and marketing company. The Company has three segments: United States antimony operations, Mexican antimony operations and United States zeolite operations. The Company's operations include a smelter and a metal refinery in Montana, and a smelter and approximately three mills in Mexico. The Company operates through Antimony Division and Zeolite Division.Antimony DivisionThe Company's antimony smelter and metals plant is located in the Burns Mining District of Sanders County, Montana. The property includes approximately two five-acre mill sites. The Company works with suppliers in North America, Central America, Europe, Australia and South America. It owns equipment and the leases on real property of United States Antimony, Mexico S.A. de C.V. (USAMSA). It has interests in Antimony de Mexico SA de CV (AM), which owns the San Miguel concession of the Los Juarez property. USAMSA has various divisions, which include the Madero smelter in Coahuila; the Puerto Blanco flotation mill and oxide circuit in Guanajuato, and mining properties that include the Los Juarez mineral deposit with concessions in Queretaro, the Wadley mining concession in San Lis Potosi, the Soyatal deposits in Queretaro, and the Guadalupe properties in Zacatecas.The Company's Montana smelter processes feed from Canadian, Mexican and Australian sources; recovers metals, and makes finished antimony oxide and metal. The Company's Madero smelter produces antimony from Mexico. The Company produces antimony metal, oxide, sodium antimonite and metals from its processing facility near Thompson Falls, Montana. The Company also sells antimony metal for use in bearings, storage batteries and ordnance.Zeolite DivisionThe Company owns Bear River Zeolite Company, (BRZ), which has a lease with Webster Farm, L.L.C., which allows BRZ to surface mine and process zeolite on property located near Preston, Idaho. In addition, BRZ has zeolite on the United States Bureau of Land Management land. The property has approximately two dryer circuits, one for lines one and two, and one for the Raymond mill. The dryer circuits include an approximately 50 ton feed bin, and each dryer has a conveyor bypass around each dryer, a bucket elevator, and a dry rock bin. Its Raymond mill circuit includes a 6058 high-side Raymond mill with a double whizzer, dust collector, approximately two 100 ton product silos, feed bin, conveyors, air slide, bucket elevators and control booth. The Raymond mill has a rated capacity of over 10 tons per hour.

» Full Overview of UAMY.A







